   &lt;br/&gt;
   Mike Kelly &#60;mikekelly321@...&#62; hat am 3. Januar 2012 um 17:57 geschrieben:
   &lt;br/&gt;
   &lt;br/&gt;
   &lt;br/&gt;
   &#62; This ability to evolve the application flow of web apps is due almost
   &lt;br/&gt;
   &#62; entirely to the sophistication of the human brain. Machine agents do
   &lt;br/&gt;
   &#62; not behave this way. If you have evidence showing they can, please
   &lt;br/&gt;
   &#62; share it.
  &lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;p style=&quot;margin: 0px;&quot;&gt;&#160;&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p style=&quot;margin: 0px;&quot;&gt;Not sure where you take this &#39;evolve the application flow of web apps&#39; from. For one, there are lots of changes that do not involve changing the order in which interactions occur (which I assume you mean by flow) and secondly, I did not mean to say that such changes would magically be enabled by REST.&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p style=&quot;margin: 0px;&quot;&gt;&#160;&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p style=&quot;margin: 0px;&quot;&gt;The thing is however, that REST enables communication to *happen* even if the intended application fails to run into a success state in the end. REST clients (i.e. HTTP clients) will be able to handle all possible kinds of error states (by virtue of implementing HTTP completely) and we will generally be able to proceed(!) from failure states at a much more sophisticated level than with a broken RPC application. The latter just dies with some convoluted exception in some log in some obscure location.&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p style=&quot;margin: 0px;&quot;&gt;&#160;&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p style=&quot;margin: 0px;&quot;&gt;For me, leveraging the power of HTTP as-is is at the heart of applying REST successfully - we need not seek for building AI into clients - that&#39;s an illusion anyhow.&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p style=&quot;margin: 0px;&quot;&gt;&#160;&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p style=&quot;margin: 0px;&quot;&gt;jan&lt;/p&gt;
